Note: ============================================================================
Note: LEXER STRUCTURE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Minimal Swift lexer state: source pointer, byte position into it,
1-based line/column for diagnostics, and the produced tokens list.
The tokens slot is stored at offset 32 but the structure is
allocated with 32 bytes (via arena_alloc) and the tokens field is
written separately by tokenize_swift after it creates the list -
so allocations stay tight while still providing a single state
record threaded through every helper.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (declared as 5 fields × 8 bytes) accessed via
memory_get/set_int64 at offsets 0/8/16/24/32 for source, position,
line, column, tokens respectively. create_swift_lexer initially
allocates 32 bytes covering source through column; tokens is
populated lazily once tokenize_swift creates the output list.
@End Implementation
Type called "SwiftLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    position as Integer         Note: Current position
    line as Integer             Note: Current line number
    column as Integer           Note: Current column number
    tokens as Integer           Note: List of tokens
End Type

@Reasoning:
Per-token record carrying type, original textual lexeme, source
position for diagnostics, and a value slot reserved for literals
that need an out-of-band parsed representation (e.g. interpolated
strings, custom numeric literals). Token values are kept opaque at
this layer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record laid out as token_type @0, lexeme @8, line @16,
column @24, value @32. Allocated by create_token via arena_alloc;
value is initialized to 0 and populated only by literal-specific
paths.
@End Implementation
Type called "SwiftToken":
    token_type as Integer       Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer           Note: Token text
    line as Integer             Note: Line number
    column as Integer           Note: Column number
    value as Integer            Note: Parsed value (for literals)
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LEXER INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The lexer is a 32-byte flat record holding (source ptr, position, line,
column) at offsets 0/8/16/24. Position starts at 0 because string_char_at is
0-indexed, but line and column start at 1 because that matches every editor
and diagnostic convention. Allocation goes through arena_alloc rather than
plain allocate because lexer state is naturally lifetime-bound to a single
parse pass; the arena owning the lexer also owns the eventual token list
attached at offset 32, so destruction is a single arena reset.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_swift_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Swift lexer

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0           Note: position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 1          Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1          Note: column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 0          Note: tokens

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The top-level tokenisation loop alternates skip_whitespace with next_token and
appends every produced token (including the final EOF) to the list stored at
offset 32 of the lexer struct. EOF is appended rather than just used as a loop
exit so downstream parsers can treat the token stream uniformly without a
separate end-of-stream check. The whitespace skip is called before each
next_token, so leading whitespace (including newlines that drive line/column
counting in advance_char) is handled outside the per-token lexers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "tokenize_swift" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize entire Swift source

    Let tokens be proc create from ListOps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, tokens

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace with lexer

        Let token be proc next_token with lexer
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc list_append from ListOps with tokens, token

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return tokens
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHARACTER HANDLING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bounded character lookahead. Returns 0 at EOF rather than throwing
so callers can use 0 as a "no character" sentinel and avoid an
extra at_eof helper.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source pointer (offset 0) and position (offset 8). Reads
source length via string_length. If position >= len, returns 0
(EOF). Otherwise returns string_char_at(source, position) - a
single byte (codepoint) as Integer.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look at current character without advancing

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    If position is greater than or equal to len:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes one character and updates position plus line/column
tracking. Detecting newline (ASCII 10) here means every consumer
gets accurate line/column for free without having to handle line
counting locally.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Peeks current via peek_char; returns 0 if at EOF. Increments
position by 1. If the consumed char was 10 (newline), increments
line and resets column to 1. Otherwise increments column. Returns
the consumed character so callers can branch on the returned
value if needed.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Move to next character

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position

    Note: Track line/column
    If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1  Note: Reset column

    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, column
    End If

    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Swift treats newlines as statement separators (`\n` is meaningful
to the grammar), so this routine deliberately stops at LF rather
than swallowing it. It also handles line comments (`//`) and
nested block comments (`/* ... */`) inline so the main dispatch
loop doesn't need separate trivia-skipping passes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop: peek_char. On 0 returns 1 (EOF). On space (32), tab (9), or
CR (13), advances and continues. On LF (10), returns 1 without
consuming so the main loop can emit a newline token. On '/' (47),
peeks_next_char; if '/' calls skip_line_comment and continues, if
'*' calls skip_block_comment and continues, otherwise returns 1
(slash is the start of an operator). Any other character returns
1 without advancing.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace characters

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        Note: Check for whitespace (space, tab, CR)
        If ch is equal to 32:  Note: Space
            proc advance_char with lexer

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 13:  Note: CR
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 10:  Note: LF (newline is significant in Swift for statement termination)
                        Note: Don't skip newlines - they're meaningful
                        Return 1

                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Check for comments
                        If ch is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
                            Let next_ch be proc peek_next_char with lexer
                            If next_ch is equal to 47:  Note: '//' line comment
                                proc skip_line_comment with lexer

                            Otherwise:
                                If next_ch is equal to 42:  Note: '/*' block comment
                                    proc skip_block_comment with lexer

                                Otherwise:
                                    Return 1  Note: Not whitespace
                                End If
                            End If

                        Otherwise:
                            Return 1  Note: Not whitespace
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two-step lookahead used by multi-character operator and comment
detection. Returns 0 past EOF for the same sentinel-friendly
reason as peek_char.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source and position. Computes len = string_length(source);
if position + 1 >= len returns 0. Otherwise returns
string_char_at(source, position + 1).
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_next_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look ahead one character

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    If position plus 1 is greater than or equal to len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Swift `//` line comments run to the end of the line. The
terminating newline is left for the dispatcher so the line counter
increments via the normal advance_char path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances twice to consume both slashes. Loops: peek_char; on 0
(EOF) returns 1; on 10 (newline) returns 1 without consuming it;
otherwise advances and continues.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip // comment until end of line

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip first /
    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip second /

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: EOF
        End If

        If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance_char with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Swift block comments NEST (unlike C-family languages), so a depth
counter is required. Encountering `/*` increments depth and `*/`
decrements it; the comment ends only when depth returns to 0. EOF
inside an unclosed comment returns 0 so the caller can recognize
the malformed comment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances past the opening `/*` (two chars). Sets depth = 1. Loops
while depth > 0:
- peek_char; on 0 (EOF) returns 0 (unclosed comment).
- on '/' (47), peek_next; if '*' (42), nested-comment-open:
  increment depth, advance twice. Otherwise advance once.
- on '*' (42), peek_next; if '/' (47), comment-close: decrement
  depth, advance twice. Otherwise advance once.
- on any other character, advance once.
Returns 1 when depth reaches 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip /* */ comment (can be nested in Swift)

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip /
    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip *

    Let depth be 1

    While depth is greater than 0:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Unclosed comment minus error
        End If

        If ch is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
            Let next_ch be proc peek_next_char with lexer
            If next_ch is equal to 42:  Note: '*' minus nested comment start
                Set depth to depth plus 1
                proc advance_char with lexer
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 42:  Note: '*'
                Set next_ch to proc peek_next_char with lexer
                If next_ch is equal to 47:  Note: '/' minus comment end
                    Set depth to depth minus 1
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If

            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOKEN CREATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The lexeme tokenizers locate a token's span by its start and end byte
positions, but the StringPrim substring primitive is length-based. This
thin adapter converts an end-exclusive [start, end) span into the
(start, length) form StringPrim.string_substring expects, computing
length as end minus start and clamping a negative span to zero so a
malformed span yields an empty lexeme rather than an out-of-range read.
@End Reasoning
Process called "swift_substring" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Let length be end_pos minus start_pos
    If length is less than 0:
        Set length to 0
    End If
    Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with source, start_pos, length
End Process

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 40-byte SwiftToken from the arena and snapshots the
lexer's current line and column so the token records the position
where its first character started. value is zero-initialized;
specialized literal tokenizers may overwrite it later (currently
none do, but the slot is reserved for that use).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 40 bytes via arena_alloc. Stores token_type @0, lexeme
@8. Reads lexer.line (offset 16) and lexer.column (offset 24),
stores at token offsets 16 and 24 respectively. Zeroes value at
offset 32. Returns the token pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes lexer as Integer, token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token structure

    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, 0  Note: value (optional)

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NEXT TOKEN
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The per-token dispatcher uses a single character of lookahead at peek_char to
decide which sub-tokeniser to invoke. NEWLINE is emitted as a distinct token
rather than silently consumed because Swift uses newlines as statement
separators in many contexts (it has no required semicolons between top-level
statements). Identifier and number tests dispatch to dedicated tokenisers that
handle multi-character runs; punctuation is recognised inline because each
character maps directly to a unique token and an inline branch is faster than
a sub-routine call.
@End Reasoning
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EOF, ""
    End If

    Note: Newline (statement terminator in Swift)
    If ch is equal to 10:
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NEWLINE, "\\n"
    End If

    Note: Identifier or keyword
    If proc is_alpha with ch:
        Return proc tokenize_identifier with lexer
    End If

    Note: Number literal
    If proc is_digit with ch:
        Return proc tokenize_number with lexer
    End If

    Note: String literal
    If ch is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
        Return proc tokenize_string with lexer
    End If

    Note: Operators and punctuation
    If ch is equal to 40:  Note: '('
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LPAREN, "("
    End If

    If ch is equal to 41:  Note: ')'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_RPAREN, ")"
    End If

    If ch is equal to 123:  Note: '{'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACE, "{"
    End If

    If ch is equal to 125:  Note: '}'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACE, "}"
    End If

    If ch is equal to 91:  Note: '['
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LBRACKET, "["
    End If

    If ch is equal to 93:  Note: ']'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_RBRACKET, "]"
    End If

    If ch is equal to 44:  Note: ','
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_COMMA, ","
    End If

    If ch is equal to 58:  Note: ':'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_COLON, ":"
    End If

    If ch is equal to 59:  Note: ';'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SEMICOLON, ";"
    End If

    If ch is equal to 64:  Note: '@'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_AT, "@"
    End If

    Note: Dot (and ranges)
    If ch is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        Return proc tokenize_dot with lexer
    End If

    Note: Plus
    If ch is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let next_ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '+='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS_EQUAL, "+="
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PLUS, "+"
    End If

    Note: Minus and arrow
    If ch is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '-='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS_EQUAL, "-="
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: '->' arrow
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ARROW, "->"
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_MINUS, "-"
    End If

    Note: Star
    If ch is equal to 42:  Note: '*'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '*='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR_EQUAL, "*="
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STAR, "*"
    End If

    Note: Slash
    If ch is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '/='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH_EQUAL, "/="
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_SLASH, "/"
    End If

    Note: Percent
    If ch is equal to 37:  Note: '%'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PERCENT, "%"
    End If

    Note: Equal
    If ch is equal to 61:  Note: '='
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '=='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQUAL_EQUAL, "=="
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EQUAL, "="
    End If

    Note: Not and Not Equal
    If ch is equal to 33:  Note: '!'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '!='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL, "!="
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_EXCLAMATION, "!"
    End If

    Note: Less
    If ch is equal to 60:  Note: '<'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '<='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL, "<="
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 60:  Note: '<<'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LSHIFT, "<<"
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_LESS, "<"
    End If

    Note: Greater
    If ch is equal to 62:  Note: '>'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 61:  Note: '>='
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, ">="
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 62:  Note: '>>'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_RSHIFT, ">>"
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_GREATER, ">"
    End If

    Note: Ampersand
    If ch is equal to 38:  Note: '&'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 38:  Note: '&&'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_AND_AND, "&&"
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_AMPERSAND, "&"
    End If

    Note: Pipe
    If ch is equal to 124:  Note: '|'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 124:  Note: '||'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_OR_OR, "||"
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_PIPE, "|"
    End If

    Note: Caret
    If ch is equal to 94:  Note: '^'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_CARET, "^"
    End If

    Note: Tilde
    If ch is equal to 126:  Note: '~'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_TILDE, "~"
    End If

    Note: Question (optional and nil-coalescing)
    If ch is equal to 63:  Note: '?'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 63:  Note: '??'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_QUESTION_QUESTION, "??"
        End If
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_QUESTION, "?"
    End If

    Note: Unknown character - error. The offending character's byte value is
    Note: preserved in the token's value slot by create_token's caller context;
    Note: the lexeme records a stable diagnostic string the parser can surface.
    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, "Unknown character"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IDENTIFIER AND KEYWORD TOKENIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Identifier scanning records the start position, consumes a run of
alphanumerics and underscores (Swift's identifier continuation set), then
slices the lexeme out of the source string. The same routine handles both
identifiers and reserved words because Swift keywords are syntactically
identifiers - they are differentiated only by lexeme comparison. We delegate
keyword recognition to check_keyword so the tokeniser does not have to know
which strings happen to be reserved; new keywords can be added there alone.
@End Reasoning
Process called "tokenize_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize identifier or keyword

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If proc is_alpha with ch:
            proc advance_char with lexer

        Otherwise:
            If proc is_digit with ch:
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc swift_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    Note: Check if keyword
    Let token_type be proc check_keyword with lexeme
    If token_type is not equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with lexer, token_type, lexeme
    End If

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Keyword recognition is a linear sequence of string_equals comparisons rather
than a hash-table lookup because Swift's keyword set is small (~50 entries)
and modern compilers can branch-predict the sequence efficiently, while the
hashtable would require an extra allocation and would force a hash on every
identifier. Returning 0 (the conventional "not a keyword" sentinel) on the
no-match fallthrough means the caller can use a plain int comparison instead
of a boolean wrapper.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is a Swift keyword

    Note: Declaration keywords
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "let":
        Return TOKEN_LET
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "var":
        Return TOKEN_VAR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "func":
        Return TOKEN_FUNC
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "class":
        Return TOKEN_CLASS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "struct":
        Return TOKEN_STRUCT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "enum":
        Return TOKEN_ENUM
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "protocol":
        Return TOKEN_PROTOCOL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "extension":
        Return TOKEN_EXTENSION
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "typealias":
        Return TOKEN_TYPEALIAS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "import":
        Return TOKEN_IMPORT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "init":
        Return TOKEN_INIT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "deinit":
        Return TOKEN_DEINIT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "subscript":
        Return TOKEN_SUBSCRIPT
    End If

    Note: Control flow keywords
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "if":
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "else":
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "guard":
        Return TOKEN_GUARD
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "switch":
        Return TOKEN_SWITCH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "case":
        Return TOKEN_CASE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "default":
        Return TOKEN_DEFAULT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "where":
        Return TOKEN_WHERE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "for":
        Return TOKEN_FOR
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "in":
        Return TOKEN_IN
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "while":
        Return TOKEN_WHILE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "repeat":
        Return TOKEN_REPEAT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "break":
        Return TOKEN_BREAK
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "continue":
        Return TOKEN_CONTINUE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "fallthrough":
        Return TOKEN_FALLTHROUGH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "return":
        Return TOKEN_RETURN
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "defer":
        Return TOKEN_DEFER
    End If

    Note: Error handling keywords
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "throw":
        Return TOKEN_THROW
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "throws":
        Return TOKEN_THROWS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "try":
        Return TOKEN_TRY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "catch":
        Return TOKEN_CATCH
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "do":
        Return TOKEN_DO
    End If

    Note: Property/method modifiers
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "get":
        Return TOKEN_GET
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "set":
        Return TOKEN_SET
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "willSet":
        Return TOKEN_WILLSET
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "didSet":
        Return TOKEN_DIDSET
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "inout":
        Return TOKEN_INOUT
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "static":
        Return TOKEN_STATIC
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "mutating":
        Return TOKEN_MUTATING
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "nonmutating":
        Return TOKEN_NONMUTATING
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "override":
        Return TOKEN_OVERRIDE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "final":
        Return TOKEN_FINAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "lazy":
        Return TOKEN_LAZY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "optional":
        Return TOKEN_OPTIONAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "required":
        Return TOKEN_REQUIRED
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "convenience":
        Return TOKEN_CONVENIENCE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "dynamic":
        Return TOKEN_DYNAMIC
    End If

    Note: Access control
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "public":
        Return TOKEN_PUBLIC
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "private":
        Return TOKEN_PRIVATE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "fileprivate":
        Return TOKEN_FILEPRIVATE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "internal":
        Return TOKEN_INTERNAL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "open":
        Return TOKEN_OPEN
    End If

    Note: Memory management
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "weak":
        Return TOKEN_WEAK
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "unowned":
        Return TOKEN_UNOWNED
    End If

    Note: Type keywords
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "self":
        Return TOKEN_SELF
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "super":
        Return TOKEN_SUPER
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "nil":
        Return TOKEN_NIL
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "true":
        Return TOKEN_TRUE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "false":
        Return TOKEN_FALSE
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "is":
        Return TOKEN_IS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "as":
        Return TOKEN_AS
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "Any":
        Return TOKEN_ANY
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "some":
        Return TOKEN_SOME
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a keyword
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: NUMBER TOKENIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The number tokeniser handles a 2-character lookahead for radix prefixes
(0x/0b/0o) before falling through to the decimal/float scanner. The decimal
loop distinguishes '.' followed by a digit (decimal point) from '.' followed
by another '.' or any non-digit (the range operator '..<' or '...') by
peeking two characters; this is critical because '1...5' must lex as
INT(1) RANGE INT(5), NOT FLOAT(1.) error. The is_float flag is set when a
decimal point is consumed so the final create_token call can emit the
correct numeric token type.
@End Reasoning
Process called "tokenize_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize number literal (integer or float)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let is_float be 0
    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer

    Note: Check for prefix (0x, 0b, 0o)
    If ch is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        Let next_ch be proc peek_next_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 120:  Note: 'x' minus hexadecimal
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc tokenize_hex_number with lexer, start_pos
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 98:  Note: 'b' minus binary
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc tokenize_binary_number with lexer, start_pos
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 111:  Note: 'o' minus octal
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc tokenize_octal_number with lexer, start_pos
        End If
    End If

    Note: Decimal number
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If proc is_digit with ch:
            proc advance_char with lexer

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 46:  Note: '.' minus decimal point
                Note: Check if next char is digit (not a range operator)
                Set next_ch to proc peek_next_char with lexer
                If proc is_digit with next_ch:
                    Set is_float to 1
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    Note: '.' not followed by a digit is a range operator, not part of the number
                    Break
                End If

            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 101:  Note: 'e' minus exponent
                    Set is_float to 1
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                    Set next_ch to proc peek_char with lexer
                    If next_ch is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    End If
                    If next_ch is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
                        proc advance_char with lexer
                    End If

                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_' minus digit separator (ignored)
                        proc advance_char with lexer

                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc swift_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL, lexeme
    End If

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex literals start with `0x` (already consumed by the caller) and
allow `_` between digits as a readability separator. The lexer
keeps underscores in the lexeme verbatim - they are stripped only
during semantic parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop:
- peek_char; if is_hex_digit, advance and continue
- on `_` (95), advance (digit separator)
- otherwise break.
After the loop, captures the lexeme via string_substring(source,
start_pos, end_pos) and emits TOKEN_INT_LITERAL.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_hex_number" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize hexadecimal number

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If proc is_hex_digit with ch:
            proc advance_char with lexer

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_' minus digit separator
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc swift_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary literals start with `0b`. Only 0, 1, and `_` are accepted
inside. Like hex literals, the underscore separator is preserved
in the lexeme for later semantic processing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop on peek_char: 48 ('0') -> advance, 49 ('1') -> advance, 95
('_') -> advance, any other character breaks. Captures the lexeme
via string_substring and emits TOKEN_INT_LITERAL.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_binary_number" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize binary number

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
            proc advance_char with lexer

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 49:  Note: '1'
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_' minus digit separator
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc swift_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lexeme
End Process

@Reasoning:
Octal literals start with `0o` and contain digits 0-7 plus
optional `_` separators. The two-level if structure with both
upper and lower octal checks keeps each branch single-purpose.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop on peek_char:
- if ch in [48..55] ('0'..'7'), advance
- else if ch == 95 ('_'), advance
- else break.
Note the implementation nests these checks so the structure
matches the surface logic: digit-range first, then underscore,
then break. Emits TOKEN_INT_LITERAL with the substring lexeme.
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_octal_number" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize octal number

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: is greater than or equal to '0'
            If ch is less than or equal to 55:  Note: is less than or equal to '7'
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_' minus digit separator
                    proc advance_char with lexer

                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End If

        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_' minus digit separator
                proc advance_char with lexer

            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let lexeme be proc swift_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_INT_LITERAL, lexeme
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRING TOKENIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
After consuming the opening quote we peek for a second and third quote to
decide between single-line and triple-quoted (multi-line) forms; triple-quoted
strings have very different termination and escape rules so we delegate to
tokenize_multiline_string. The single-line scanner treats backslash-escapes
as a two-char sequence (advance for the backslash, advance for whatever
follows) without attempting to decode the escape - decoding happens later when
the token's lexeme is materialised for HIR. An unterminated string returns a
TOKEN_ERROR rather than panicking so the parser can surface a diagnostic and
keep scanning the rest of the file.
@End Reasoning
Process called "tokenize_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize string literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    proc advance_char with lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    Note: Check for multi-line string (triple quotes)
    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
    If ch is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
        Let next_ch be proc peek_next_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
            Note: Triple-quoted string
            proc advance_char with lexer
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc tokenize_multiline_string with lexer, start_pos
        End If
    End If

    Note: Regular string
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set ch to proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, "Unterminated string"
        End If

        If ch is equal to 10:  Note: Newline (error in single-line string)
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, "Newline in string literal"
        End If

        If ch is equal to 34:  Note: '"' - closing quote
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let lexeme be proc swift_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL, lexeme
        End If

        If ch is equal to 92:  Note: '\\' minus escape sequence
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Let escaped_ch be proc peek_char with lexer
            If escaped_ch is not equal to 0:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If

        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char with lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, "Unterminated string"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Swift multi-line strings use triple double-quotes `"""..."""`.
Detection of the closing triple uses a quote_count counter that
increments on each `"` and resets on any non-quote character; a
count of 3 indicates the close. This approach handles strings that
contain runs of one or two quote characters without false matches.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets quote_count = 0. Loops on peek_char:
- 0 (EOF) returns TOKEN_ERROR "Unterminated multi-line string"
- 34 ('"'): increments quote_count, advances. If quote_count
  reaches 3, captures the lexeme via string_substring from
  start_pos to current end_pos and emits TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL.
- any other char: resets quote_count to 0. If 92 ('\\') advances
  to consume the escape character and the next character. Otherwise
  advances one.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Operates on untrusted source. The unclosed-string path emits
TOKEN_ERROR rather than crashing or producing an unbounded lexeme,
and escape consumption never reads past EOF because peek_char
returns 0 there.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tokenize_multiline_string" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize multi-line string literal (triple quotes)

    Let quote_count be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, "Unterminated multi-line string"
        End If

        If ch is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
            Set quote_count to quote_count plus 1
            proc advance_char with lexer
            If quote_count is equal to 3:
                Note: Found closing triple quotes
                Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
                Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let lexeme be proc swift_substring with source, start_pos, end_pos
                Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL, lexeme
            End If

        Otherwise:
            Set quote_count to 0
            If ch is equal to 92:  Note: '\\' minus escape
                proc advance_char with lexer
                Let escaped_ch be proc peek_char with lexer
                If escaped_ch is not equal to 0:
                    proc advance_char with lexer
                End If

            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char with lexer
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, "Unterminated multi-line string"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DOT TOKENIZATION (and range operators)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Swift has three dot-leading tokens: `.` (member access), `...`
(closed range), `..<` (half-open range). The lexer recognizes
them at lex time so the parser doesn't have to disambiguate.
Plain `..` is invalid in Swift; if seen it emits TOKEN_ERROR
rather than producing a wrong-but-plausible token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances past the first `.`. peek_char:
- 46 ('.'): advances past second `.`, peek_char:
  - 46: advances past third `.`, emits TOKEN_DOT_DOT_DOT "..."
  - 60 ('<'): advances past `<`, emits TOKEN_DOT_DOT_LESS "..<"
  - otherwise: emits TOKEN_ERROR "Invalid operator '..'"
- otherwise: emits TOKEN_DOT "."
@End Implementation
Process called "tokenize_dot" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize dot, range operators (..., ..<)

    proc advance_char with lexer
    Let ch be proc peek_char with lexer

    If ch is equal to 46:  Note: Second '.'
        proc advance_char with lexer
        Let next_ch be proc peek_char with lexer
        If next_ch is equal to 46:  Note: Third '.' minus closed range '...'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOT_DOT_DOT, "..."
        End If
        If next_ch is equal to 60:  Note: '<' minus half-open range '..<'
            proc advance_char with lexer
            Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOT_DOT_LESS, "..<"
        End If
        Note: Just '..' - not valid in Swift, but return error token
        Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR, "Invalid operator '..'"
    End If

    Return proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_DOT, "."
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHARACTER CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Identifier-friendly alpha predicate. Includes ASCII upper, lower,
and `_` because Swift identifiers start with these. Unicode
identifier characters that Swift formally supports are not yet
handled here (the lexer is ASCII-only at present); the underscore
is included so swift identifier-start works uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if ch in [65..90] ('A'..'Z'), [97..122] ('a'..'z'), or
ch == 95 ('_'). Otherwise 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: is greater than or equal to 'A'
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:  Note: is less than or equal to 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: is greater than or equal to 'a'
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:  Note: is less than or equal to 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Decimal digit predicate used by number tokenizers and the
fractional/exponent parts of float literals. Restricted to ASCII
0-9 because Swift numeric literals don't accept other digit
shapes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if ch in [48..57] ('0'..'9'). Otherwise 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: is greater than or equal to '0'
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:  Note: is less than or equal to '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Hex predicate used inside 0x... literals. Calls is_digit first
(so 0-9 short-circuit), then tests A-F and a-f ranges. Case
preservation is the parser's concern; this predicate accepts
either.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if is_digit(ch), ch in [65..70] ('A'..'F'), or ch in
[97..102] ('a'..'f'). Otherwise 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_hex_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hexadecimal digit

    If proc is_digit with ch:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: is greater than or equal to 'A'
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:  Note: is less than or equal to 'F'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: is greater than or equal to 'a'
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:  Note: is less than or equal to 'f'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process
